<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900814-0046</DOCNO><DOCID>900814-0046.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Sony's U.S. Unit to Develop   A New Unix Generation   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/14/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SNE</CO><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- Sony Corp.'s U.S. unit will set up an engineeringgroup to develop the next generation of the Unix operatingsystem, widely used in engineering workstations, a companyspokesman said.   A group of about 30 engineers will be set up within SonyCorp. of America in October to produce a more advancedversion of the Unix operating system, the spokesman said.Aside from about four engineers sent from Japan, the staffwill consist almost entirely of local engineers experiencedin working with Unix, the spokesman for the electronicsconcern said.</LP><TEXT>   Sony will be one of the first Japanese companies todevelop Unix software applications in the U.S., allowing thecompany to take advantage of advanced U.S. softwaretechnology and expertise, the spokesman said.   &quot;Workstations is the area in which competition is the mostintense and the pace of developing new products is thefastest in the computer-related industry,&quot; he said.   Establishment of the software developing group in the U.S.will allow Sony to keep pace with technological developments,he said.   Computer software-related operations in the U.S. by otherJapanese companies center on converting U.S.-made applicationsoftware so that it can be loaded onto their own computers,the spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>